{"title_page": "Bolin (The Legend of Korra)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Bolin (''The Legend of Korra'')}}\n{{Infobox character\n| image            = Bolin (The Legend of Korra).jpg\n| name             = Bolin\n| series           = [[The Legend of Korra]]\n| first            = \"[[A Leaf in the Wind]]\" (2012)\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Michael Dante DiMartino]]<br/>[[Bryan Konietzko]]\n| portrayer        =\n| voice            = [[P. J. Byrne]]\n| gender           = Male\n| occupation       = Pro-bender (Seasons 1-2)<br />Actor (Season 2)<br />Soldier (Season 4)<br />Police officer (''[[The Legend of Korra: Turf Wars|Turf Wars]]'')\n| family           = San (father)<br />Naoki (mother)<br />[[Mako (The Legend of Korra)|Mako]] (brother)\n| significant_other = [[The Legend of Korra#Opal|Opal]] (girlfriend, Seasons 3-4)<br />[[The Legend of Korra#Eska|Eska]] (girlfriend, ex-fianc\u00e9, Season 2)\n| relatives        = Chow (paternal uncle)<br />LiLing (aunt)<br />Chow Jr. (first cousin)<br />Tu (first cousin)<br />Meng-Meng (first cousin)<br />'''[[Kinship care|Grandfamily]]''':<br />Bohai (paternal grandfather)<br />Yin (paternal grandmother)\n| nationality      = United Republic of Nations\n| lbl21            = Bending element \n| data21           = '''Primary''': {{hlist|[[Earth (classical element)|Earthbending]]}}'''Sub-styles''': {{hlist|Lavabending}}\n| lbl22            = Age <!-- Age, hair and eye color parameters for fictional characters are controversial and in most cases have been deprecated--> \n| data22           = 16 (Book One)<br />17 (Books 2-3)<br />20 (Book 4)\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Bolin'''|\u613d\u6797|B\u00f3 L\u00edn}} is a major fictional character in [[Nickelodeon]]'s [[List of animated television series|animated television series]] ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'', which aired from 2012 to 2014. The character and the series, a sequel to ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'', were created by [[Michael Dante DiMartino]] and [[Bryan Konietzko]]. He is voiced by [[P. J. Byrne]]. Bolin is able to manipulate the classical element of earth, which is known as earthbending. It is revealed in the [[The Legend of Korra (season 3)|third season]] that he is also able to create and control [[lava]], which is a very rare sub-ability called lavabending.\n\n==Character overview==\nBolin (\u613d\u6797, in in-universe orthography) is an earthbender from a multicultural family who grew up on the streets of Republic City as an orphan with his older brother, [[Mako (The Legend of Korra)|Mako]]. As an earthbender, Bolin has the ability to move and shape [[earth (classical element)|earth]] at will. However, he knows a rare subset of earthbending called lavabending, allowing him to manipulate [[lava]], turning it into earth and back. As a friend of Avatar [[Korra]], the character often plays the role of [[comic relief]] within ''The Legend of Korra'', taking over [[Sokka]]'s role in ''[[The Last Airbender]]''. Bolin is characterized as being somewhat dimwitted, but having a \"heart of gold.\" His enthusiastic personality led him to becoming an [[actor]]. Furthermore, much like Sokka, Bolin has had relationships with various young female characters within the show.<ref name=\"Rebel Spirit\">{{cite episode|title= Rebel Spirit|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=201|airdate=2013-09-13|season=2|number=1|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=201|transcript=Transcript for 201 \u2013 Rebel Spirit|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Night of a Thousand Stars\">{{cite episode|title= Night of a Thousand Stars|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=211|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=211| transcript=Transcript for 211 \u2013 Night of a Thousand Stars|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n==Creation and conception==\n[[File:P. J. Byrne by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|left|[[P.J. Byrne]] voices Bolin.]]\n\nAccording to Bryan Konietzko, Bolin's character was inspired by the original concept of [[Toph Beifong]], who was going to be a male character Konietzko described as \"kind of a big, not sharpest tool in the shed.\" When Toph's character was decided to be a smaller girl, the creators still had many ideas for the male earthbender, which they implemented into Bolin.<ref>{{cite speech|title=Transcript:San Diego Comic-Con 2011|last=Konietzko|first=Bryan|date=2011|event=Comic-Con|location=San Diego }}</ref>\n\nBolin along with his older brother Mako were designed by Ryu Ki-Hyun.<ref name=\"Racebending.com\">{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Marissa|title= Legend of Korra Panel at ComicCon 2011|url=http://www.racebending.com/v4/featured/the-legend-of-korra-panel-at-comiccon-2011/|accessdate=28 January 2015|work=Racebending.com|date=28 July 2011}}</ref> The character went through a series of design changes in its development. Joaquim Dos Santos originally wanted both characters to have strong noses, however the idea was nixed. It was decided that as the younger brother, Bolin's character would have a somewhat simplistic and naive view of the world, while Mako's character as the older brother and provider for the two, would be more cynical and serious in nature.<ref name=DiMartino>{{cite book |author1=DiMartino, Michael |author2=Konietzko, Bryan |author3=Dos Santos, Joaquim | year=2013 | chapter=Early Development | title=The Legend of Korra\u2014The Art of the Animated Series, Book One: Air| publisher= Dark Horse Comics| isbn=1-61655-168-2}}</ref>\n\nBolin and Mako live in Republic City, a \u201cmodern metropolis\u201d in the United Republic.  According to the creators, the United Republic was founded by Aang and Zuko after the Hundred Year War as a place where benders and non-Benders from all four Kingdoms could live in harmony. Mako and Bolin were created in part to highlight the radical changes that had occurred in the seventy years since the end of the war, specifically the ethnic diversity and blending of cultures of the various nations in the United Republic. The two are the sons of an Earth Kingdom father and a Fire Nation mother. Because of the heritages of their parents, Bolin is an earthbender and Mako is a firebender.<ref name=\"Racebending.com\"/>\n\n===Voice actor===\nBolin is voiced by [[P.J. Byrne]]. Bryne related to the character as he explained, \"I\u2019m a people person, I\u2019m a peoplely people, and I think that\u2019s what my character is.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/tv/legend-of-korra-mako-bolin-voice-actors-talk-book-2-spirits/|title=\u2018Legend of Korra': Mako, Bolin voice actors talk \u2018Book 2: Spirits\u2019|date=September 11, 2013|publisher=Hero Complex}}</ref> Fellow ''The Legend of Korra'' voice actor [[David Faustino]], who voiced Mako, said during the show's run that while they were all given \"some freedom\", Bryne especially as he was \"sort of the comic relief of the show\" and that much of his material was improv which would either be kept or cut depending on how it was received.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://comicsalliance.com/janet-varney-david-faustino-legend-of-korra-interview/ |title=Janet Varney and David Faustino Talk 'Legend of Korra' |first=Juliet |last=Kahn |publisher=ComicsAlliance |date=August 11, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906125001/http://comicsalliance.com/janet-varney-david-faustino-legend-of-korra-interview/ |archivedate=September 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===''The Legend of Korra''===\n\n====''Book One: Air''====\nIn Season One, Bolin was initially infatuated with [[Korra]]. He befriended her showing her pro-bending tricks.<ref name=\"A Leaf in the Wind\">{{cite episode|title= A Leaf in the Wind|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=102|airdate=2012-04-14|season=1|number=2|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=102|transcript=Transcript for 102 - A Leaf in The Wind|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> When the team needed to come up with thirty thousand yuans to enter the pro-bending Championship, Bolin accepted Shady Shin's offer to work for the local criminal underworld. He along with four [[Triad (organized crime)|triad]] members was kidnapped and taken before Amon, leader of the Equalists, a revolutionary movement dedicated to removing bending from all benders. Bolin was rescued by Mako and Korra.<ref name=\"The Revelation\">{{cite episode|title= The Revelation|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=103|transcript=Transcript for 103 \u2013 The Revelation|airdate=2012-04-21|season=1|number=3|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=103|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Bolin would take Korra on a date, although his feelings were unrequited. Later Amon and his Equalists destroyed the pro-bending arena, leaving Bolin and Mako homeless.<ref name=\"And the Winner Is...\">{{cite episode|title= And the Winner Is...|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=106|airdate=2012-05-12|season=1|number=6|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=106|transcript=Transcript for 106 \u2013 And the Winner Is... |credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> [[Asami Sato|Asami]] offered them a place to stay. However, after Hiroshi Sato was revealed as an Equalist, the brothers and Asami moved to Air Temple Island with Korra.<ref name=\"The Aftermath\">{{cite episode|title= The Aftermath|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=107|airdate=2012-05-19|season=1|number=7|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=107|transcript=Transcript for 107 \u2013 The Aftermath|credits=Director:Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writers:Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> After Bolin and his brother were arrested for allegedly interfering with police activities, [[Lin Beifong]] freed the two,<ref name=\"When Extremes Meet\">{{cite episode|title= When Extremes Meet|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=108|airdate=2012-06-02|season=1|number=8|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=108|transcript=Transcript for 108 \u2013 When Extremes Meet|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> who informed them that Korra was kidnapped. After finding Korra, Amon launched a large-scale attack on the city. \"Team Avatar\" (Korra, Mako, Bolin and Asami) was forced to retreat into the tunnel system of the city, where they would await the arrival of reinforcements.<ref name=\"Turning the Tides\">{{cite episode|title= Turning the Tides|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=110|airdate=2012-06-16|season=1|number=10|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=110|transcript=Transcript for 110 \u2013 Turning the Tides|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themarysue.com/the-legend-of-korra-newbie-recap-turning-the-tides/|title=The Legend of Korra Newbie Recap: \"Turning the Tides\"|first=Rebecca|last=Pahle|publisher=The Mary Sue|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> After the reinforcements were overwhelmed by the Equalists [[biplane]]s, the team split up, and Bolin accompanied Asami to an Equalist airfield in order to stop the planes from flying.<ref name=\"Skeletons in the Closet\">{{cite episode|title= Skeletons in the Closet|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=111|airdate=2012-06-23|season=1|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=111|transcript=Transcript for 111 \u2013 Skeletons in the Closet|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> They would eventually destroy the airfield capturing Hiroshi Sato in the process.<ref name=\"Endgame\">{{cite episode|title= Endgame|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=112|airdate=2012-06-23|season=1|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=112|transcript=Transcript for 112 \u2013 Endgame|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n====''Book Two: Spirits''====\n\nIn Season Two, after the Anti-bending Revolution, Bolin accompanied Team Avatar to the Southern Water Tribe. He became romantically involved with Korra's cousin, Eska, a macabrely domineering princess from the Northern Water Tribe, who was visiting her southern counterparts.<ref name=\"Rebel Spirit\"/> Bolin soon found the relationship borderline abusive and intended to break up with the princess. However, when he tried to do so, Eska engaged herself to him. Bolin secretly left the Southern Water Tribe for Republic City, avoiding an angered and deranged Eska in the process.<ref name=\"The Southern Lights\">{{cite episode|title= The Southern Lights|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=202|airdate=2013-09-13|season=2|number=2|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=202| transcript=Transcript for 202 \u2013 Southern Lights|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Civil Wars, Part 1\">{{cite episode|title= Civil Wars, Part 1|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=203|airdate=2013-09-20|season=2|number=3|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=203| transcript=Transcript for 203 \u2013 Civil Wars, Part 1|credits=Director:Colin Heck; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Civil Wars, Part 2\">{{cite episode|title= Civil Wars, Part 2|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=204|airdate=2013-09-27|season=2|number=4|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=204| transcript=Transcript for 204 \u2013 Civil Wars, Part 2|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later, Bolin was cast to play Nuktuk, the male lead in the businessman Varrick's film The Adventures of Nuktuk: Hero of the South.<ref name=\"Peacekeepers\">{{cite episode|title= Peacekeepers, Part 2|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=205|airdate=2013-10-04|season=2|number=5|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=205| transcript=Transcript for 205 \u2013 Peacekeepers|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> The movie was a success and Bolin enjoyed fame and fortune. On the night of the final screening of the film, Bolin thwarted a kidnapping of President Raiko. Despite being outnumbered by the would-be kidnappers, Bolin overpowered them. He forced one of them to reveal who his employer was, thus exposing Varrick's duplicity.<ref name=\"Night of A Thousand Stars\">{{cite episode|title= Night of A Thousand Stars|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=211|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=211| transcript=Transcript for 211 \u2013Night of A Thousand Stars|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later Bolin rejoined Team Avatar at the South Pole.<ref name=\"Harmonic Convergence\">{{cite episode|title= Harmonic Convergence|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=212|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=212| transcript=Transcript for 212 \u2013 Harmonic Convergence|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> At the end of Season 2, Bolin assisted in the efforts to keep a multitude of evil spirits away from Korra's meditating body in the Tree of Time while the Avatar defeated the Dark Avatar. Bolin had an unlikely ally in this effort in Eska and at one point admitted his love for the princess, who in turn kissed him. Before they were completely overrun by the evil spirits, Korra's returning spirit nullified the threat. After the crisis ended, Bolin suggested to Eska that she live with him at Republic City. However, Eska declined, confessing that she was only caught up in the moment when she kissed him. She told Bolin that he would have a special place \"in the organ that pumps [her] blood\".<ref name=\"Darkness Falls\">{{cite episode|title= Darkness Falls|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=213|airdate=2013-11-22|season=2|number=13|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=213| transcript=Transcript for 213 \u2013 Darkness Falls|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Light in the Dark\">{{cite episode|title= Light in the Dark|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=214|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=14|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=214| transcript=Transcript for 214 \u2013 Light in the Dark|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n====''Book Three: Change''====\nIn Season Three, Bolin would accompany Team Avatar as well as [[Tenzin (The Legend of Korra)|Tenzin]] and Bumi, in their quest to find new airbenders in the Earth Kingdom to help recreate the Air Nation. Initially they enjoyed limited success.<ref name=\"Rebirth\">{{cite episode|title= Rebirth|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=302|airdate=2014-06-27|season=3|number=2|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=302| transcript=Transcript for 302 \u2013 Rebirth|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> However at the Earth Kingdom capital of Ba Sing Se, the group discovered that a number of airbenders were imprisoned by the Earth Queen. While in the capital Mako and Bolin reunited with their extended family, who resided in the city.<ref name=\"Earth Queen\">{{cite episode|title= Earth Queen|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=303|airdate=2014-06-27|season=3|number=3|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=303| transcript=Transcript for 303 \u2013 Earth Queen|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> The group would successfully liberate the captive airbenders who all agreed to join the Air Nation.<ref name=\"In Harm's Way\">{{cite episode|title= In Harm's Way|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=304|airdate=2014-07-11|season=3|number=4|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=304| transcript=Transcript for 304 \u2013 In Harm\u2019s Way|credits=Director:Melchior Zwyer; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>  Team Avatar traveled to the Earth Kingdom city of Zaofu to recruit one more known airbender, Lin Beifong's niece Opal. When Bolin met Opal, the two almost immediately fell in love, beginning a romantic relationship. Opal agreed to join the Air Nation, and departed Zaofu to join the nascent Air Nation at the Northern Air Temple.<ref name=\"Old Wounds\">{{cite episode|title= Old Wounds|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=306|airdate=2014-07-18|season=3|number=6|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=306| transcript=Transcript for 306 \u2013 Old Wounds|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Katie Mattila|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later Bolin and Mako would find themselves locked in the first of a series of battles with [[Zaheer|Zaheer's]] Red Lotus allies Ming-Hua and Ghazan. The earthbender was routed by Ghazan and the brothers were captured. The brothers were transported to Ba Sing Se, where there was a bounty on the two for aiding the airbenders\u2019 escape,<ref name=\"The Stakeout\">{{cite episode|title= The Stakeout|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=309|airdate=2014-08-01|season=3|number=9|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=309| transcript=Transcript for 309 \u2013 The Stakeout|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> and incarcerated. After Zaheer murdered the Earth Queen, ushering a period of anarchy in the capital, Zaheer allowed every prisoner to escape except Bolin and Mako. Zaheer  informed the two that they would be freed, but only after they agreed to relay a message to Korra.<ref name=\"Long Live the Queen\">{{cite episode|title= Long Live the Queen|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=310|airdate=2014-08-08|season=3|number=10|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=310| transcript=Transcript for 310 \u2013 Long Live the Queen|credits=Director:Melchoir Zwyer; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>  The two commandeered an airship and subsequently rescued their extended family from their burning house. They reunited with Korra and Asami where Mako relayed Zaheer\u2019s message to Korra: Zaheer and other members of the Red Lotus planned to travel to the Northern Air Temple to eliminate the Air Nation unless Korra surrendered to him.<ref name=\"Ultimatum\">{{cite episode|title= Ultimatum|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=311|airdate=2014-08-15|season=3|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=311| transcript=Transcript for 311 \u2013 Ultimatum|credits=Director:Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> The Avatar agreed to surrender to the Red Lotus in exchange for the Air Nation, who were being held captive by the Red Lotus. When it became apparent that the Red Lotus double-crossed the group; Bolin and Mako attempted to battle Ghazan and Ming-Hua, but Ghazan utilized his lavabending to trap the brothers. Facing certain death in the collapsing temple which was being consumed by lava, Bolin miraculously discovered that he, like Ghazan, could lavabend. Coupled with the timely appearance of Kai on his baby bison, Lefty, the brothers were able to escape the doomed Northern Air Temple.<ref name=\"Enter the Void\">{{cite episode|title= Enter the Void|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=312|airdate=2014-08-22|season=3|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=312| transcript=Transcript for 312 \u2013 Enter the Void|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later the brothers would be locked in yet another battle with Ming-Hua and Ghazan, with Bolin once again battling Ghazan, this time in a cave. With Bolin utilizing his newly found lavabending abilities, the two were much more evenly matched. However, when Ghazan began to gain the upper hand Mako, having dispatched Ming-Hua, joined the fray. When it became apparent that Ghazan was no match for the two, the lavabender collapsed the entire cave on the three. Ghazan died in the process while the brothers safely escaped.<ref name=\"Venom of the Red Lotus\">{{cite episode|title= Venom of the Red Lotus|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=313|airdate=2014-08-22|season=3|number=13|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=313| transcript=Transcript for 313 \u2013 Venom of the Red Lotus|credits=Director:Melchior Zwyer; Writer:Joshua Hamilton, Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n====''Book Four: Balance''====\n[[File:Opal kissing Bolin on the cheek.png|thumb|275 px|left|Opal kissing Bolin on the cheek as a sign of forgiveness for his actions while working for Kuvira.]]\n\nDuring the fourth season, Bolin began working to re-unite the Earth Kingdom under [[Kuvira]], who would become the season's villain. During this season, he was stuck between being loyal to his boss or to his friends, where he believed that Kuvira was doing the right thing despite his friends trying to convince him otherwise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/legend-korra-book-4-spoilers-bolin-taken-prisoner-episode-5-what-happened-enemy-gates-1717084|title='The Legend Of Korra' Book 4 Spoilers: Bolin Taken Prisoner In Episode 5; What Happened In 'Enemy At The Gates'? [RECAP]|publisher=International Business news|last=Garofalo|first=Alex|date=2014-10-31}}</ref> Later in the season, the character realized that Kuvira was going too far and escaped her control.<ref name=\"Reunion\">{{cite web|url=http://screencrush.com/legend-of-korra-review-reunion/|title=\u2018The Legend of Korra\u2019 Book 4 Review: \"Reunion\"|publisher=Screen Crush|last=Patches|first=Matt|date=2014-11-14}}</ref> By helping saving the family of his girlfriend Opal, Bolin regained her trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/legend-korra-operation-beifong-212678|title=The Legend Of Korra: \"Operation Beifong\"|publisher=A.V. Club|last=Sava|first=Oliver|date=2014-12-05}}</ref> After returning to Republic City, Bolin along with Lin, Suyin, and Zhu Li, interrupted a conference of President Raiko's, who was meeting with Korra, Prince Wu, Tenzin and Mako. Zhu Li informed everyone that Kuvira planned to attack Republic City in two weeks. The President ordered the evacuation of Republic City while Bolin, along with the rest of team Avatar, decided to launch a preemptive strike against Kuvira in an attempt to destroy the dictator's superweapon. However their mission was unsuccessful, discovering the army was only hours away from Republic city, a week earlier than expected, They also were surprised that Kuvira mounted her superweapon on a 25-story tall robot, which she controlled through her metalbending. The team briefed their allies on Kuvira's progress.<ref name=\"Kuvira's Gambit\">{{cite episode|title= Kuvira's Gambit|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=411|airdate=2014-12-12|season=4|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=411| transcript=Transcript for 411 \u2013 Kuvira\u2019s Gambit|credits=Director:Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> After Kuvira's army arrived in Republic City, Bolin took part in a plan to stop the large robot: the benders would relentlessly attack the robot to distract Kuvira while two hummingbird mecha suits would cut a circular hole in the machine without being crushed. A team would then enter the suit through the hole and ultimately destroy the massive machine from its inside. The plan was generally successful as he managed to enter inside the hole with Suyin, Lin, Mako, and Korra.<ref name=\"Day of the Colossus\">{{cite episode|title= Day of the Colossus|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=412|airdate=2014-12-19|season=4|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=412| transcript=Transcript for 412 \u2013 Day of the Colossus|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> In the process Bolin saved Mako from certain death, carrying his brother to safety after he found him unconscious in the engine room of the crumbling machine. In the series' end, Bolin would preside over Varrick (who he befriended in Season Four) and Zhu Li's wedding at Air Temple Island.<ref name=\"The Last Stand\">{{cite episode|title= The Last Stand|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=413|airdate=2014-12-19|season=4|number=13|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=413| transcript=Transcript for 413 \u2013 The Last Stand|credits=Director:Melchior Zwyer; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n===Graphic novel trilogy===\n{{main|The Legend of Korra: Turf Wars}}\nIn part one, Bolin is now a police officer on Chief [[Lin Beifong]]'s triad task force, with Mako serving as his temporary partner. After breaking up a fight between the Triple Threat and the Creeping Crystal triads,  Bolin and Mako arrest Two-Toed Ping. Bolin and Mako reunite with Korra and Asami, who have returned from their vacation in the Spirit World. The reunion is cut short when the Air Nomads are attacked by Triple Threats at the Spirit Portal. Bolin comes to Mako's rescue when he loses a fight with the Triple Threat's new leader, Tokuga, but Tokuga is able to get away. In the aftermath of the battle, Korra kisses Asami out of relief, leading to Bolin, Mako, Jinora and Opal discovering their relationship.\n\n====The Legend of Korra: Ruins of the Empire====\n{{main|The Legend of Korra: Ruins of the Empire}}\nIn part one of the graphic novel continuation of the series, Bolin is now Secretary to the President of the United Republic.\n\n===Outside of ''The Legend of Korra''===\nTogether with his brother Mako, Bolin starred in \"Republic City Hustle\", the first of three character-focused shorts Nickelodeon released in advance of the September premiere of the second season. In this short, a younger Mako and Bolin are shown living on the street, where they \"enter the crime-ridden underworld of Republic City.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geek-news.mtv.com/2013/08/09/legend-of-korra-new-short/|title=Mako and Bolin Are The Criminal Element In This 'Legend of Korra' Web Short|publisher=[[MTV]]|last=Webb|first=Charles|date=2013-09-08}}</ref>\n\nBolin appears in ''[[The Legend of Korra: A New Era Begins]]'' as a playable character.\n\nBolin appears in ''The Legend of Korra'' books ''Revolution''<ref>{{cite book|title=Revolution|publisher=Random House Books for Young Readers|isbn=978-0449815540|year=2013|first=Erica|last=Arthur}}</ref> and ''Endgame'', two novels that together adapt the first season of the series.<ref>{{cite book|title=Endgame|publisher=Random House Books for Young Readers|isbn=978-0449817346|year=2013|first=Erica|last=Arthur}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nBolin was generally well received by press and fans alike. The character's backstory was commended, with the three part prequel to the series, \"Republic City Hustle\" praised for sensitively depicting Bolin and his brother's Mako difficult childhood.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schick|first1=Michal|title=\u2018The Legend of Korra\u2019 webseries \u2018Republic City Hustle\u2019 concludes|url=http://www.hypable.com/the-legend-of-korra-webseries-republic-city-hustle-concludes/|accessdate=25 January 2015|work=Hypable|date=23 August 2013}}</ref> The depiction of the strong relationship between Mako and Bolin in the series also drew praise with the scene where Mako gives his grandmother his red scarf described as \"an unbelievably powerful moment shared by [Mako], Bolin, and their family\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hillman|first1=Kevin|title=Depth of characters drives strong third Korra season|url=http://www.curiata.com/content/3733.php|accessdate=25 January 2015|work=Hypable|date=24 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128114503/http://www.curiata.com/content/3733.php|archivedate=28 January 2015}}</ref> [[Tor.com]] editor Moddicai Knode praised Bolin's role in the episode \"Operation Beifong\", seeing it as the start of his character arc. According to Knode, here Bolin finally became as good as a character as [[Sokka]] was in the original series. Knode states that it was clear from the start that Bolin was designed to be a similar character to that of Sokka, but he states that \"you can\u2019t just provide a bit of comedic relief and call yourself the Sokka of the group.\" Knode claims that to be \"the Sokka of the group,\" Bolin needed enough character growth, to be \"the man with the plan\" and, optionally, be the character with the most romantic development on the show. Knode praises how the character of Bolin makes bold, risky decisions while acknowledging when he makes a mistake, and that despite not being the \"sharpest pencil in the box,\" he makes up for this by teamwork and \"stepping up to the plate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2014/12/the-legend-of-korra-book-4-episode-10-operation-beifong|title=\"Operation Beifong\" Strikes Back on The Legend of Korra!|publisher=Tor.com|last=Knode|first=Moddicai}}</ref>\n\nMatt Patches of ScreenCrush compared Bolin and Varrick's escape in the season four episode \"Reunion\" to the 2008 film ''[[Defiance (2008 film)|Defiance]]'', where the characters are \"blasting their way through [enemies] as they survived in the woods.\" Patches enjoyed the comedy in the dialogue between Bolin and Varrick, but also comments that \"there\u2019s a tremendous amount of moral insight too.\"<ref name=\"Reunion\" /> Reviewer Michael Mammano of [[Den of Geek]] also praised Bolin's role in this episode, pointing out the \"sense of authority and competence he\u2019s developed\" and noting that he is \"far more poised and precise\" than in previous seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/legend-of-korra/241314/the-legend-of-korra-reunion-review|title=The Legend of Korra: Reunion Review|publisher=Den of Geek|last=Mammano|first=Michael|date=2014-11-14}}</ref> P.J. Byrne also drew praise for his frenetic voicework, with reviewer Oliver Sava noting that Byrne's performance helped convincingly reflect the character's occasionally \"chaotic\" mindset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/legend-korra-battle-zaofu-211583|title=The Legend Of Korra: \"Battle Of Zaofu\"|publisher=A.V. Club|last=Sava|first=Oliver|date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nBolin's relationship with \"ice princess\" Eska during season two has been criticized for playing an [[abusive relationship]] for laughs, with a scene where Eska forcefully separates Bolin and his friend Korra being brought up often as an example.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thoughtsonliberty.com/nickelodeons-the-legend-of-korra-makes-light-of-abusive-women-and-thats-not-okay|title=Nickelodeon\u2019s \"The Legend of Korra\" Makes Light of Abusive Women, and That\u2019s Not Okay|publisher=Thoughtsonliberty|last=Lurttrell|first=Gina|date=2013-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btchflcks.com/2013/09/why-the-legend-of-korra-is-still-a-feminists-headache.html#.VLzjDYd-y3A|title=Why \u2018The Legend of Korra\u2019 is (Still) a Feminist\u2019s Headache|publisher=Bitch Flicks|last=Tatum|first=Erin|date=2013-09-19}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the series, reviewer William Cannon of the Latin Times listed a number of characters from ''The Legend of Korra'' series who he felt would be suitable to have the lead role in a spin-off series. Bolin and Mako as co-leads made his list, with the reviewer commenting that \"the funny awkward brother and the more serious brooding bro\" would make \"sitcom magic\". Cannon felt that the two brothers had the best chemistry on ''The Legend of Korra''. He also believed the fact that the two characters were \"powerful benders\" would make the spin-off series interesting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latintimes.com/legend-korra-season-4-series-finale-6-characters-who-should-receive-spinoff-series-274236|title=\u2018Legend Of Korra\u2019 Season 4 Series Finale: 6 Characters Who Should Receive Spinoff Series|date=November 7, 2014|first=William|last=Cannon|publisher=Latin Times}}</ref> In response to Cannon's article, Adam Bellotto of ''Venture Capital Post'' was more reserved in his assessment of Bolin and Mako co-starring in a spin-off series. While he agreed with Cannon that a spin-off series focusing on the brothers would work well, Bellotto felt that such a series would be unoriginal. He held that either a new character or an underdeveloped character from the series was most appropriate to star in a spin-off.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vcpost.com/articles/44830/20150224/legend-of-korra-character-perfect-spin-series-movie-release-cards.htm|title=Which \"Legend of Korra\" character would be perfect for a Spin-Off series? Movie release might be in the cards|date=February 24, 2015|publisher=Venture Capital Post|first=Adam|last=Bellotto}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Do not add any fanfic/fanon or fanart websites -->\n* [http://nick.com/legend-of-korra/ Official TV Show Website] at [[Nickelodeon (TV channel)#Nick.com|Nick.com]]\n* [http://www.nick.com/legend-of-korra/bolin-earthbender/ Bolin] at Nick.com\n\n{{Avatar: The Last Airbender|state=expanded}}\n{{Portal bar|Nickelodeon|Animation|Television}}\n\n[[Category:The Legend of Korra]]\n[[Category:Avatar: The Last Airbender characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2012]]\n[[Category:Fictional Hung Ga practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional N\u00e1n T\u00e1ngl\u00e1ng practitioners]]\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with fire or heat abilities]]<!--\"Lavabending\"-subtyle-->\n[[Category:Fictional characters with earth or stone abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional actors]]\n[[Category:Fictional soldiers]]\n[[Category:Fictional male sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Male characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Bolin (''The Legend of Korra'')}}\n{{Infobox character\n| image            = Bolin (The Legend of Korra).jpg\n| name             = Bolin\n| series           = [[The Legend of Korra]]\n| first            = \"[[A Leaf in the Wind]]\"\n| last             = \n| creator          = [[Michael Dante DiMartino]]<br/>[[Bryan Konietzko]]\n| portrayer        =\n| voice            = [[P. J. Byrne]]\n| gender           = Male\n| occupation       = Pro-bender (Seasons 1-2)<br />Actor (Season 2)<br />Soldier (Season 4)<br />Police officer (''[[The Legend of Korra: Turf Wars|Turf Wars]]'')\n| family           = San (father)<br />Naoki (mother)<br />[[Mako (The Legend of Korra)|Mako]] (brother)\n| significant_other = [[The Legend of Korra#Opal|Opal]] (girlfriend, Seasons 3-4)<br />[[The Legend of Korra#Eska|Eska]] (girlfriend, ex-fianc\u00e9, Season 2)\n| relatives        = Chow (paternal uncle)<br />LiLing (aunt)<br />Chow Jr. (first cousin)<br />Tu (first cousin)<br />Meng-Meng (first cousin)<br />'''[[Kinship care|Grandfamily]]''':<br />Bohai (paternal grandfather)<br />Yin (paternal grandmother)\n| nationality      = United Republic of Nations\n| lbl21            = Bending element \n| data21           = '''Primary''': {{hlist|[[Earth (classical element)|Earthbending]]}}'''Sub-styles''': {{hlist|Lavabending}}\n| lbl22            = Age <!-- Age, hair and eye color parameters for fictional characters are controversial and in most cases have been deprecated--> \n| data22           = 16 (Book One)<br />17 (Books 2-3)<br />20 (Book 4)\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Bolin'''|\u613d\u6797|B\u00f3 L\u00edn}} is a major fictional character in [[Nickelodeon]]'s [[List of animated television series|animated television series]] ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'', which aired from 2012 to 2014. The character and the series, a sequel to ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'', were created by [[Michael Dante DiMartino]] and [[Bryan Konietzko]]. He is voiced by [[P. J. Byrne]]. Bolin is able to manipulate the classical element of earth, which is known as earthbending. It is revealed in the [[The Legend of Korra (season 3)|third season]] that he is also able to create and control [[lava]], which is a very rare sub-ability called lavabending.\n\n==Character overview==\nBolin (\u613d\u6797, in in-universe orthography) is an earthbender from a multicultural family who grew up on the streets of Republic City as an orphan with his older brother, [[Mako (The Legend of Korra)|Mako]]. As an earthbender, Bolin has the ability to move and shape [[earth (classical element)|earth]] at will. However, he knows a rare subset of earthbending called lavabending, allowing him to manipulate [[lava]], turning it into earth and back. As a friend of Avatar [[Korra]], the character often plays the role of [[comic relief]] within ''The Legend of Korra'', taking over [[Sokka]]'s role in ''[[The Last Airbender]]''. Bolin is characterized as being somewhat dimwitted, but having a \"heart of gold.\" His enthusiastic personality led him to becoming an [[actor]]. Furthermore, much like Sokka, Bolin has had relationships with various young female characters within the show.<ref name=\"Rebel Spirit\">{{cite episode|title= Rebel Spirit|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=201|airdate=2013-09-13|season=2|number=1|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=201|transcript=Transcript for 201 \u2013 Rebel Spirit|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Night of a Thousand Stars\">{{cite episode|title= Night of a Thousand Stars|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=211|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=211| transcript=Transcript for 211 \u2013 Night of a Thousand Stars|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n==Creation and conception==\n[[File:P. J. Byrne by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|left|[[P.J. Byrne]] voices Bolin.]]\n\nAccording to Bryan Konietzko, Bolin's character was inspired by the original concept of [[Toph Beifong]], who was going to be a male character Konietzko described as \"kind of a big, not sharpest tool in the shed.\" When Toph's character was decided to be a smaller girl, the creators still had many ideas for the male earthbender, which they implemented into Bolin.<ref>{{cite speech|title=Transcript:San Diego Comic-Con 2011|last=Konietzko|first=Bryan|date=2011|event=Comic-Con|location=San Diego }}</ref>\n\nBolin along with his older brother Mako were designed by Ryu Ki-Hyun.<ref name=\"Racebending.com\">{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Marissa|title= Legend of Korra Panel at ComicCon 2011|url=http://www.racebending.com/v4/featured/the-legend-of-korra-panel-at-comiccon-2011/|accessdate=28 January 2015|work=Racebending.com|date=28 July 2011}}</ref> The character went through a series of design changes in its development. Joaquim Dos Santos originally wanted both characters to have strong noses, however the idea was nixed. It was decided that as the younger brother, Bolin's character would have a somewhat simplistic and naive view of the world, while Mako's character as the older brother and provider for the two, would be more cynical and serious in nature.<ref name=DiMartino>{{cite book |author1=DiMartino, Michael |author2=Konietzko, Bryan |author3=Dos Santos, Joaquim | year=2013 | chapter=Early Development | title=The Legend of Korra\u2014The Art of the Animated Series, Book One: Air| publisher= Dark Horse Comics| isbn=1-61655-168-2}}</ref>\n\nBolin and Mako live in Republic City, a \u201cmodern metropolis\u201d in the United Republic.  According to the creators, the United Republic was founded by Aang and Zuko after the Hundred Year War as a place where benders and non-Benders from all four Kingdoms could live in harmony. Mako and Bolin were created in part to highlight the radical changes that had occurred in the seventy years since the end of the war, specifically the ethnic diversity and blending of cultures of the various nations in the United Republic. The two are the sons of an Earth Kingdom father and a Fire Nation mother. Because of the heritages of their parents, Bolin is an earthbender and Mako is a firebender.<ref name=\"Racebending.com\"/>\n\n===Voice actor===\nBolin is voiced by [[P.J. Byrne]]. Bryne related to the character as he explained, \"I\u2019m a people person, I\u2019m a peoplely people, and I think that\u2019s what my character is.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/tv/legend-of-korra-mako-bolin-voice-actors-talk-book-2-spirits/|title=\u2018Legend of Korra': Mako, Bolin voice actors talk \u2018Book 2: Spirits\u2019|date=September 11, 2013|publisher=Hero Complex}}</ref> Fellow ''The Legend of Korra'' voice actor [[David Faustino]], who voiced Mako, said during the show's run that while they were all given \"some freedom\", Bryne especially as he was \"sort of the comic relief of the show\" and that much of his material was improv which would either be kept or cut depending on how it was received.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://comicsalliance.com/janet-varney-david-faustino-legend-of-korra-interview/ |title=Janet Varney and David Faustino Talk 'Legend of Korra' |first=Juliet |last=Kahn |publisher=ComicsAlliance |date=August 11, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906125001/http://comicsalliance.com/janet-varney-david-faustino-legend-of-korra-interview/ |archivedate=September 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===''The Legend of Korra''===\n\n====''Book One: Air''====\nIn Season One, Bolin was initially infatuated with [[Korra]]. He befriended her showing her pro-bending tricks.<ref name=\"A Leaf in the Wind\">{{cite episode|title= A Leaf in the Wind|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=102|airdate=2012-04-14|season=1|number=2|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=102|transcript=Transcript for 102 - A Leaf in The Wind|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> When the team needed to come up with thirty thousand yuans to enter the pro-bending Championship, Bolin accepted Shady Shin's offer to work for the local criminal underworld. He along with four [[Triad (organized crime)|triad]] members was kidnapped and taken before Amon, leader of the Equalists, a revolutionary movement dedicated to removing bending from all benders. Bolin was rescued by Mako and Korra.<ref name=\"The Revelation\">{{cite episode|title= The Revelation|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=103|transcript=Transcript for 103 \u2013 The Revelation|airdate=2012-04-21|season=1|number=3|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=103|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Bolin would take Korra on a date, although his feelings were unrequited. Later Amon and his Equalists destroyed the pro-bending arena, leaving Bolin and Mako homeless.<ref name=\"And the Winner Is...\">{{cite episode|title= And the Winner Is...|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=106|airdate=2012-05-12|season=1|number=6|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=106|transcript=Transcript for 106 \u2013 And the Winner Is... |credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> [[Asami Sato|Asami]] offered them a place to stay. However, after Hiroshi Sato was revealed as an Equalist, the brothers and Asami moved to Air Temple Island with Korra.<ref name=\"The Aftermath\">{{cite episode|title= The Aftermath|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=107|airdate=2012-05-19|season=1|number=7|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=107|transcript=Transcript for 107 \u2013 The Aftermath|credits=Director:Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writers:Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> After Bolin and his brother were arrested for allegedly interfering with police activities, [[Lin Beifong]] freed the two,<ref name=\"When Extremes Meet\">{{cite episode|title= When Extremes Meet|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=108|airdate=2012-06-02|season=1|number=8|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=108|transcript=Transcript for 108 \u2013 When Extremes Meet|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> who informed them that Korra was kidnapped. After finding Korra, Amon launched a large-scale attack on the city. \"Team Avatar\" (Korra, Mako, Bolin and Asami) was forced to retreat into the tunnel system of the city, where they would await the arrival of reinforcements.<ref name=\"Turning the Tides\">{{cite episode|title= Turning the Tides|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=110|airdate=2012-06-16|season=1|number=10|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=110|transcript=Transcript for 110 \u2013 Turning the Tides|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themarysue.com/the-legend-of-korra-newbie-recap-turning-the-tides/|title=The Legend of Korra Newbie Recap: \"Turning the Tides\"|first=Rebecca|last=Pahle|publisher=The Mary Sue|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> After the reinforcements were overwhelmed by the Equalists [[biplane]]s, the team split up, and Bolin accompanied Asami to an Equalist airfield in order to stop the planes from flying.<ref name=\"Skeletons in the Closet\">{{cite episode|title= Skeletons in the Closet|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=111|airdate=2012-06-23|season=1|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=111|transcript=Transcript for 111 \u2013 Skeletons in the Closet|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> They would eventually destroy the airfield capturing Hiroshi Sato in the process.<ref name=\"Endgame\">{{cite episode|title= Endgame|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=112|airdate=2012-06-23|season=1|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=112|transcript=Transcript for 112 \u2013 Endgame|credits=Director: Joaquim Dos Santos, Ki Hyun Ryu; Writer: Michael Dante DiMartino, Bryan Konietzko |series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n====''Book Two: Spirits''====\n\nIn Season Two, after the Anti-bending Revolution, Bolin accompanied Team Avatar to the Southern Water Tribe. He became romantically involved with Korra's cousin, Eska, a macabrely domineering princess from the Northern Water Tribe, who was visiting her southern counterparts.<ref name=\"Rebel Spirit\"/> Bolin soon found the relationship borderline abusive and intended to break up with the princess. However, when he tried to do so, Eska engaged herself to him. Bolin secretly left the Southern Water Tribe for Republic City, avoiding an angered and deranged Eska in the process.<ref name=\"The Southern Lights\">{{cite episode|title= The Southern Lights|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=202|airdate=2013-09-13|season=2|number=2|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=202| transcript=Transcript for 202 \u2013 Southern Lights|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Civil Wars, Part 1\">{{cite episode|title= Civil Wars, Part 1|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=203|airdate=2013-09-20|season=2|number=3|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=203| transcript=Transcript for 203 \u2013 Civil Wars, Part 1|credits=Director:Colin Heck; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Civil Wars, Part 2\">{{cite episode|title= Civil Wars, Part 2|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=204|airdate=2013-09-27|season=2|number=4|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=204| transcript=Transcript for 204 \u2013 Civil Wars, Part 2|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later, Bolin was cast to play Nuktuk, the male lead in the businessman Varrick's film The Adventures of Nuktuk: Hero of the South.<ref name=\"Peacekeepers\">{{cite episode|title= Peacekeepers, Part 2|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=205|airdate=2013-10-04|season=2|number=5|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=205| transcript=Transcript for 205 \u2013 Peacekeepers|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> The movie was a success and Bolin enjoyed fame and fortune. On the night of the final screening of the film, Bolin thwarted a kidnapping of President Raiko. Despite being outnumbered by the would-be kidnappers, Bolin overpowered them. He forced one of them to reveal who his employer was, thus exposing Varrick's duplicity.<ref name=\"Night of A Thousand Stars\">{{cite episode|title= Night of A Thousand Stars|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=211|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=211| transcript=Transcript for 211 \u2013Night of A Thousand Stars|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later Bolin rejoined Team Avatar at the South Pole.<ref name=\"Harmonic Convergence\">{{cite episode|title= Harmonic Convergence|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=212|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=212| transcript=Transcript for 212 \u2013 Harmonic Convergence|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> At the end of Season 2, Bolin assisted in the efforts to keep a multitude of evil spirits away from Korra's meditating body in the Tree of Time while the Avatar defeated the Dark Avatar. Bolin had an unlikely ally in this effort in Eska and at one point admitted his love for the princess, who in turn kissed him. Before they were completely overrun by the evil spirits, Korra's returning spirit nullified the threat. After the crisis ended, Bolin suggested to Eska that she live with him at Republic City. However, Eska declined, confessing that she was only caught up in the moment when she kissed him. She told Bolin that he would have a special place \"in the organ that pumps [her] blood\".<ref name=\"Darkness Falls\">{{cite episode|title= Darkness Falls|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=213|airdate=2013-11-22|season=2|number=13|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=213| transcript=Transcript for 213 \u2013 Darkness Falls|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Light in the Dark\">{{cite episode|title= Light in the Dark|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=214|airdate=2013-11-15|season=2|number=14|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=214| transcript=Transcript for 214 \u2013 Light in the Dark|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n====''Book Three: Change''====\nIn Season Three, Bolin would accompany Team Avatar as well as [[Tenzin (The Legend of Korra)|Tenzin]] and Bumi, in their quest to find new airbenders in the Earth Kingdom to help recreate the Air Nation. Initially they enjoyed limited success.<ref name=\"Rebirth\">{{cite episode|title= Rebirth|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=302|airdate=2014-06-27|season=3|number=2|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=302| transcript=Transcript for 302 \u2013 Rebirth|credits=Director: Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> However at the Earth Kingdom capital of Ba Sing Se, the group discovered that a number of airbenders were imprisoned by the Earth Queen. While in the capital Mako and Bolin reunited with their extended family, who resided in the city.<ref name=\"Earth Queen\">{{cite episode|title= Earth Queen|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=303|airdate=2014-06-27|season=3|number=3|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=303| transcript=Transcript for 303 \u2013 Earth Queen|credits=Director: Ian Graham; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> The group would successfully liberate the captive airbenders who all agreed to join the Air Nation.<ref name=\"In Harm's Way\">{{cite episode|title= In Harm's Way|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=304|airdate=2014-07-11|season=3|number=4|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=304| transcript=Transcript for 304 \u2013 In Harm\u2019s Way|credits=Director:Melchior Zwyer; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>  Team Avatar traveled to the Earth Kingdom city of Zaofu to recruit one more known airbender, Lin Beifong's niece Opal. When Bolin met Opal, the two almost immediately fell in love, beginning a romantic relationship. Opal agreed to join the Air Nation, and departed Zaofu to join the nascent Air Nation at the Northern Air Temple.<ref name=\"Old Wounds\">{{cite episode|title= Old Wounds|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=306|airdate=2014-07-18|season=3|number=6|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=306| transcript=Transcript for 306 \u2013 Old Wounds|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Katie Mattila|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink=The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later Bolin and Mako would find themselves locked in the first of a series of battles with [[Zaheer|Zaheer's]] Red Lotus allies Ming-Hua and Ghazan. The earthbender was routed by Ghazan and the brothers were captured. The brothers were transported to Ba Sing Se, where there was a bounty on the two for aiding the airbenders\u2019 escape,<ref name=\"The Stakeout\">{{cite episode|title= The Stakeout|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=309|airdate=2014-08-01|season=3|number=9|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=309| transcript=Transcript for 309 \u2013 The Stakeout|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> and incarcerated. After Zaheer murdered the Earth Queen, ushering a period of anarchy in the capital, Zaheer allowed every prisoner to escape except Bolin and Mako. Zaheer  informed the two that they would be freed, but only after they agreed to relay a message to Korra.<ref name=\"Long Live the Queen\">{{cite episode|title= Long Live the Queen|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=310|airdate=2014-08-08|season=3|number=10|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=310| transcript=Transcript for 310 \u2013 Long Live the Queen|credits=Director:Melchoir Zwyer; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>  The two commandeered an airship and subsequently rescued their extended family from their burning house. They reunited with Korra and Asami where Mako relayed Zaheer\u2019s message to Korra: Zaheer and other members of the Red Lotus planned to travel to the Northern Air Temple to eliminate the Air Nation unless Korra surrendered to him.<ref name=\"Ultimatum\">{{cite episode|title= Ultimatum|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=311|airdate=2014-08-15|season=3|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=311| transcript=Transcript for 311 \u2013 Ultimatum|credits=Director:Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> The Avatar agreed to surrender to the Red Lotus in exchange for the Air Nation, who were being held captive by the Red Lotus. When it became apparent that the Red Lotus double-crossed the group; Bolin and Mako attempted to battle Ghazan and Ming-Hua, but Ghazan utilized his lavabending to trap the brothers. Facing certain death in the collapsing temple which was being consumed by lava, Bolin miraculously discovered that he, like Ghazan, could lavabend. Coupled with the timely appearance of Kai on his baby bison, Lefty, the brothers were able to escape the doomed Northern Air Temple.<ref name=\"Enter the Void\">{{cite episode|title= Enter the Void|url= http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=312|airdate=2014-08-22|season=3|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=312| transcript=Transcript for 312 \u2013 Enter the Void|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> Later the brothers would be locked in yet another battle with Ming-Hua and Ghazan, with Bolin once again battling Ghazan, this time in a cave. With Bolin utilizing his newly found lavabending abilities, the two were much more evenly matched. However, when Ghazan began to gain the upper hand Mako, having dispatched Ming-Hua, joined the fray. When it became apparent that Ghazan was no match for the two, the lavabender collapsed the entire cave on the three. Ghazan died in the process while the brothers safely escaped.<ref name=\"Venom of the Red Lotus\">{{cite episode|title= Venom of the Red Lotus|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=313|airdate=2014-08-22|season=3|number=13|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=313| transcript=Transcript for 313 \u2013 Venom of the Red Lotus|credits=Director:Melchior Zwyer; Writer:Joshua Hamilton, Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n====''Book Four: Balance''====\n[[File:Opal kissing Bolin on the cheek.png|thumb|275 px|left|Opal kissing Bolin on the cheek as a sign of forgiveness for his actions while working for Kuvira.]]\n\nDuring the fourth season, Bolin began working to re-unite the Earth Kingdom under [[Kuvira]], who would become the season's villain. During this season, he was stuck between being loyal to his boss or to his friends, where he believed that Kuvira was doing the right thing despite his friends trying to convince him otherwise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/legend-korra-book-4-spoilers-bolin-taken-prisoner-episode-5-what-happened-enemy-gates-1717084|title='The Legend Of Korra' Book 4 Spoilers: Bolin Taken Prisoner In Episode 5; What Happened In 'Enemy At The Gates'? [RECAP]|publisher=International Business news|last=Garofalo|first=Alex|date=2014-10-31}}</ref> Later in the season, the character realized that Kuvira was going too far and escaped her control.<ref name=\"Reunion\">{{cite web|url=http://screencrush.com/legend-of-korra-review-reunion/|title=\u2018The Legend of Korra\u2019 Book 4 Review: \"Reunion\"|publisher=Screen Crush|last=Patches|first=Matt|date=2014-11-14}}</ref> By helping saving the family of his girlfriend Opal, Bolin regained her trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/legend-korra-operation-beifong-212678|title=The Legend Of Korra: \"Operation Beifong\"|publisher=A.V. Club|last=Sava|first=Oliver|date=2014-12-05}}</ref> After returning to Republic City, Bolin along with Lin, Suyin, and Zhu Li, interrupted a conference of President Raiko's, who was meeting with Korra, Prince Wu, Tenzin and Mako. Zhu Li informed everyone that Kuvira planned to attack Republic City in two weeks. The President ordered the evacuation of Republic City while Bolin, along with the rest of team Avatar, decided to launch a preemptive strike against Kuvira in an attempt to destroy the dictator's superweapon. However their mission was unsuccessful, discovering the army was only hours away from Republic city, a week earlier than expected, They also were surprised that Kuvira mounted her superweapon on a 25-story tall robot, which she controlled through her metalbending. The team briefed their allies on Kuvira's progress.<ref name=\"Kuvira's Gambit\">{{cite episode|title= Kuvira's Gambit|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=411|airdate=2014-12-12|season=4|number=11|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=411| transcript=Transcript for 411 \u2013 Kuvira\u2019s Gambit|credits=Director:Colin Heck; Writer:Joshua Hamilton|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> After Kuvira's army arrived in Republic City, Bolin took part in a plan to stop the large robot: the benders would relentlessly attack the robot to distract Kuvira while two hummingbird mecha suits would cut a circular hole in the machine without being crushed. A team would then enter the suit through the hole and ultimately destroy the massive machine from its inside. The plan was generally successful as he managed to enter inside the hole with Suyin, Lin, Mako, and Korra.<ref name=\"Day of the Colossus\">{{cite episode|title= Day of the Colossus|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=412|airdate=2014-12-19|season=4|number=12|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=412| transcript=Transcript for 412 \u2013 Day of the Colossus|credits=Director:Ian Graham; Writer:Tim Hedrick|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref> In the process Bolin saved Mako from certain death, carrying his brother to safety after he found him unconscious in the engine room of the crumbling machine. In the series' end, Bolin would preside over Varrick (who he befriended in Season Four) and Zhu Li's wedding at Air Temple Island.<ref name=\"The Last Stand\">{{cite episode|title= The Last Stand|url=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/episodes.php?num=413|airdate=2014-12-19|season=4|number=13|transcripturl=http://korra.avatarspirit.net/transcripts.php?num=413| transcript=Transcript for 413 \u2013 The Last Stand|credits=Director:Melchior Zwyer; Writer:Michael Dante DiMartino|series=The Legend of Korra|serieslink= The Legend of Korra|network=[[Nickelodeon]]}}</ref>\n\n===Graphic novel trilogy===\n{{main|The Legend of Korra: Turf Wars}}\nIn part one, Bolin is now a police officer on Chief [[Lin Beifong]]'s triad task force, with Mako serving as his temporary partner. After breaking up a fight between the Triple Threat and the Creeping Crystal triads,  Bolin and Mako arrest Two-Toed Ping. Bolin and Mako reunite with Korra and Asami, who have returned from their vacation in the Spirit World. The reunion is cut short when the Air Nomads are attacked by Triple Threats at the Spirit Portal. Bolin comes to Mako's rescue when he loses a fight with the Triple Threat's new leader, Tokuga, but Tokuga is able to get away. In the aftermath of the battle, Korra kisses Asami out of relief, leading to Bolin, Mako, Jinora and Opal discovering their relationship.\n\n====The Legend of Korra: Ruins of the Empire====\n{{main|The Legend of Korra: Ruins of the Empire}}\nIn part one of the graphic novel continuation of the series, Bolin is now Secretary to the President of the United Republic.\n\n===Outside of ''The Legend of Korra''===\nTogether with his brother Mako, Bolin starred in \"Republic City Hustle\", the first of three character-focused shorts Nickelodeon released in advance of the September premiere of the second season. In this short, a younger Mako and Bolin are shown living on the street, where they \"enter the crime-ridden underworld of Republic City.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geek-news.mtv.com/2013/08/09/legend-of-korra-new-short/|title=Mako and Bolin Are The Criminal Element In This 'Legend of Korra' Web Short|publisher=[[MTV]]|last=Webb|first=Charles|date=2013-09-08}}</ref>\n\nBolin appears in ''[[The Legend of Korra: A New Era Begins]]'' as a playable character.\n\nBolin appears in ''The Legend of Korra'' books ''Revolution''<ref>{{cite book|title=Revolution|publisher=Random House Books for Young Readers|isbn=978-0449815540|year=2013|first=Erica|last=Arthur}}</ref> and ''Endgame'', two novels that together adapt the first season of the series.<ref>{{cite book|title=Endgame|publisher=Random House Books for Young Readers|isbn=978-0449817346|year=2013|first=Erica|last=Arthur}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nBolin was generally well received by press and fans alike. The character's backstory was commended, with the three part prequel to the series, \"Republic City Hustle\" praised for sensitively depicting Bolin and his brother's Mako difficult childhood.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schick|first1=Michal|title=\u2018The Legend of Korra\u2019 webseries \u2018Republic City Hustle\u2019 concludes|url=http://www.hypable.com/the-legend-of-korra-webseries-republic-city-hustle-concludes/|accessdate=25 January 2015|work=Hypable|date=23 August 2013}}</ref> The depiction of the strong relationship between Mako and Bolin in the series also drew praise with the scene where Mako gives his grandmother his red scarf described as \"an unbelievably powerful moment shared by [Mako], Bolin, and their family\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hillman|first1=Kevin|title=Depth of characters drives strong third Korra season|url=http://www.curiata.com/content/3733.php|accessdate=25 January 2015|work=Hypable|date=24 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128114503/http://www.curiata.com/content/3733.php|archivedate=28 January 2015}}</ref> [[Tor.com]] editor Moddicai Knode praised Bolin's role in the episode \"Operation Beifong\", seeing it as the start of his character arc. According to Knode, here Bolin finally became as good as a character as [[Sokka]] was in the original series. Knode states that it was clear from the start that Bolin was designed to be a similar character to that of Sokka, but he states that \"you can\u2019t just provide a bit of comedic relief and call yourself the Sokka of the group.\" Knode claims that to be \"the Sokka of the group,\" Bolin needed enough character growth, to be \"the man with the plan\" and, optionally, be the character with the most romantic development on the show. Knode praises how the character of Bolin makes bold, risky decisions while acknowledging when he makes a mistake, and that despite not being the \"sharpest pencil in the box,\" he makes up for this by teamwork and \"stepping up to the plate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2014/12/the-legend-of-korra-book-4-episode-10-operation-beifong|title=\"Operation Beifong\" Strikes Back on The Legend of Korra!|publisher=Tor.com|last=Knode|first=Moddicai}}</ref>\n\nMatt Patches of ScreenCrush compared Bolin and Varrick's escape in the season four episode \"Reunion\" to the 2008 film ''[[Defiance (2008 film)|Defiance]]'', where the characters are \"blasting their way through [enemies] as they survived in the woods.\" Patches enjoyed the comedy in the dialogue between Bolin and Varrick, but also comments that \"there\u2019s a tremendous amount of moral insight too.\"<ref name=\"Reunion\" /> Reviewer Michael Mammano of [[Den of Geek]] also praised Bolin's role in this episode, pointing out the \"sense of authority and competence he\u2019s developed\" and noting that he is \"far more poised and precise\" than in previous seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/legend-of-korra/241314/the-legend-of-korra-reunion-review|title=The Legend of Korra: Reunion Review|publisher=Den of Geek|last=Mammano|first=Michael|date=2014-11-14}}</ref> P.J. Byrne also drew praise for his frenetic voicework, with reviewer Oliver Sava noting that Byrne's performance helped convincingly reflect the character's occasionally \"chaotic\" mindset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/legend-korra-battle-zaofu-211583|title=The Legend Of Korra: \"Battle Of Zaofu\"|publisher=A.V. Club|last=Sava|first=Oliver|date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nBolin's relationship with \"ice princess\" Eska during season two has been criticized for playing an [[abusive relationship]] for laughs, with a scene where Eska forcefully separates Bolin and his friend Korra being brought up often as an example.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thoughtsonliberty.com/nickelodeons-the-legend-of-korra-makes-light-of-abusive-women-and-thats-not-okay|title=Nickelodeon\u2019s \"The Legend of Korra\" Makes Light of Abusive Women, and That\u2019s Not Okay|publisher=Thoughtsonliberty|last=Lurttrell|first=Gina|date=2013-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.btchflcks.com/2013/09/why-the-legend-of-korra-is-still-a-feminists-headache.html#.VLzjDYd-y3A|title=Why \u2018The Legend of Korra\u2019 is (Still) a Feminist\u2019s Headache|publisher=Bitch Flicks|last=Tatum|first=Erin|date=2013-09-19}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the series, reviewer William Cannon of the Latin Times listed a number of characters from ''The Legend of Korra'' series who he felt would be suitable to have the lead role in a spin-off series. Bolin and Mako as co-leads made his list, with the reviewer commenting that \"the funny awkward brother and the more serious brooding bro\" would make \"sitcom magic\". Cannon felt that the two brothers had the best chemistry on ''The Legend of Korra''. He also believed the fact that the two characters were \"powerful benders\" would make the spin-off series interesting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latintimes.com/legend-korra-season-4-series-finale-6-characters-who-should-receive-spinoff-series-274236|title=\u2018Legend Of Korra\u2019 Season 4 Series Finale: 6 Characters Who Should Receive Spinoff Series|date=November 7, 2014|first=William|last=Cannon|publisher=Latin Times}}</ref> In response to Cannon's article, Adam Bellotto of ''Venture Capital Post'' was more reserved in his assessment of Bolin and Mako co-starring in a spin-off series. While he agreed with Cannon that a spin-off series focusing on the brothers would work well, Bellotto felt that such a series would be unoriginal. He held that either a new character or an underdeveloped character from the series was most appropriate to star in a spin-off.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vcpost.com/articles/44830/20150224/legend-of-korra-character-perfect-spin-series-movie-release-cards.htm|title=Which \"Legend of Korra\" character would be perfect for a Spin-Off series? Movie release might be in the cards|date=February 24, 2015|publisher=Venture Capital Post|first=Adam|last=Bellotto}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Do not add any fanfic/fanon or fanart websites -->\n* [http://nick.com/legend-of-korra/ Official TV Show Website] at [[Nickelodeon (TV channel)#Nick.com|Nick.com]]\n* [http://www.nick.com/legend-of-korra/bolin-earthbender/ Bolin] at Nick.com\n\n{{Avatar: The Last Airbender|state=expanded}}\n{{Portal bar|Nickelodeon|Animation|Television}}\n\n[[Category:The Legend of Korra]]\n[[Category:Avatar: The Last Airbender characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2012]]\n[[Category:Fictional Hung Ga practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional N\u00e1n T\u00e1ngl\u00e1ng practitioners]]\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with fire or heat abilities]]<!--\"Lavabending\"-subtyle-->\n[[Category:Fictional characters with earth or stone abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional actors]]\n[[Category:Fictional soldiers]]\n[[Category:Fictional male sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Male characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n", "name_user": "Horseradishy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bolin_(The_Legend_of_Korra)"}
{"title_page": "Lawrence J. DeLucas", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP primary sources|date=September 2011}}\n{{no footnotes|date=September 2011}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| name          =Lawrence DeLucas\n| image         =Lawrence DeLucas.jpg\n| type          =NASA Payload Specialist\n| nationality   =American\n| birth_date    =July 11, 1950\n| birth_place   =[[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| occupation    =[[Biochemist]]\n| time          =13d 19h 30m\n| mission       =[[STS-50]]\n| insignia      =[[Image:Sts-50-patch.png|60px]]\n|}}\n'''Lawrence James \"Larry\" DeLucas'''  (O. D., Ph.D.) is an American [[biochemist]] who flew aboard NASA  [[Space Shuttle]] mission [[STS-50]] as a [[Payload Specialist]].  He was born on July 11, 1950 in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and is currently married with three children.  His recreational interests include [[basketball]], [[scuba diving]], [[bowling]], [[Scale model|model]] [[airplane]]s, [[astronomy]] and [[Reading (activity)|reading]].\n\n==Education==\nDeLucas attended the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] (UAB), in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Alabama]] and received the following degrees:\n*[[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Chemistry]] (1972)\n*[[Master of Science]] degree in [[Chemistry]] (1974)\n*[[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[physiological optics|Physiological Optics]] (1979)\n*[[Doctorate]] in [[Optometry]] (1981)\n*[[Doctorate]] in [[Biochemistry]] (1982)\n\n==Organizations==\nDeLucas has served as a member of the following organizations:\n*[[American Crystallographic Association]]\n*[[American Academy of Optometry]]\n*[[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]]\n*[[Alabama Optometric Association]]\n*[[American Association of Pharmaceutical Scientists]]\n*[[National Aeronautic Association]]\n*[[Biotechnology Industry Organization]]\n*[[Biotechnology Association of Alabama]]\n*[[Helen Keller Eye Research Foundation]]\n\n==Publications==\nHe has published 163 research articles in refereed scientific journals, is co-author of 2 books, and co-inventor on 43 patents.\n\n==Honors==\n* Co-Chair, Spacehab Science Advisory Board\n* Secretary of the Board, Council of Biotechnology Centers, Biotechnology Industry Council\n* Distinguished Faculty Lecturer, UAB\n* Howell Heflin Statesmanship Award for Technology, NASA Space Flight Medal\n* Recognized as one of the scientists who could shape the 21st century in an article by [[The Sunday Times]] entitled \"The Brains Behind the 21st Century\"\n* Distinguished Crystallography Lecturer for Pittsburgh Diffraction Society Lecturers\n* Honorary Doctor of Science degree, The Ohio State University, Illinois College of Optometry, State University of New York State College of Optometry, and Ferris State University, Big Rapids, MI.\n* NASA Space Flight Medal; flew as a payload specialist astronaut on the Columbia Space Shuttle, June 25-July 9, 1992. This was the longest space shuttle flight to date making 221 orbits of Earth.  \n* Served as the NASA Chief Scientist for the International Space Station, at NASA HQ in Washington DC; 1994\u20131995.\n* Received the 1st Distinguished Alumnus Award from the University of Alabama at Birmingham, December 8, 1991.\n\n==Experience==\n* 1975 \u2013 1976: Research Associate in the Institute of Dental Research, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1977 \u2013 1982: Graduate Student, working on combined doctoral degrees in Optometry and Biochemistry\n* 1982 \u2013 2016: Member of Vision Science Research Center\n* 1983 \u2013 2016: Member, Graduate Faculty, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1984 \u2013 2016: Scientist, Comprehensive Cancer Center, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1986 \u2013 1992: Associate Director, Center for Macromolecular Crystallography, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1987 \u2013 2001: Member of NASA Science Advisory Committee for Advanced Protein Crystal Growth\n* 1989 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Materials Science, [[University of Alabama in Huntsville]], [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]], [[University of Alabama]]\n* 1989 \u2013 2016: Professor, Department of Optometry, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1990 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Laboratory of Medical Genetics, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1990 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Department of Biochemistry, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1990 \u2013 2010: Member, Executive Committee and Board of the Helen Keller Eye Research Foundation\n* 1994 \u2013 1995: NASA Chief Scientist for International Space Station\n* 1994 \u2013 2016: Director, Center for Biophysical Sciences and Engineering, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1994 \u2013 2016: Director, Cancer Center X-ray Core Facility, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1996 \u2013 2016: Member Research Foundation and Technology Transfer Committee, [[University of Alabama at \nBirmingham|UAB]]\n* 1997 \u2013 1998: Member Metabolic Bone Disease, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1997 \u2013 2000: Member, Media Relations Group, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 2001 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Physiology and Biophysics\n* 2016\u2013present: Principal Scientist, The Aerospace Corporation\n\n==Spaceflight==\n[[File:Crewmembers in the spacelab with the Lower Body Negative Pressure Study.jpg|thumb|right|DeLucas and [[Bonnie J. Dunbar]] in Spacelab with the Lower Body Negative Pressure device]]\nDeLucas was a member of the crew of [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']] for STS-50 (June 25-July 9, 1992), the United States Microgravity Laboratory-1 (USML-1) Spacelab mission. Over a two-week period, the crew conducted a wide variety of experiments relating to materials processing and fluid physics. At mission conclusion, DeLucas had traveled over 5.7 million miles in 221 Earth orbits, and had logged over 331 hours in space.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/PS/delucas.html NASA bio of DeLucas]\n*[http://www.spacefacts.de//bios/astronauts/english/delucas_lawrence.htm Spacefacts biography of Lawrence J. DeLucas]\n\n{{Use American English|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delucas, Lawrence J.}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama at Birmingham alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama in Huntsville faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Syracuse, New York]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:Space Shuttle program astronauts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP primary sources|date=September 2011}}\n{{no footnotes|date=September 2011}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2011}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| name          =Lawrence DeLucas\n| image         =Lawrence DeLucas.jpg\n| type          =NASA Payload Specialist\n| nationality   =American\n| birth_date    =July 11, 1950\n| birth_place   =[[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| occupation    =[[Biochemist]]\n| time          =13d 19h 30m\n| mission       =[[STS-50]]\n| insignia      =[[Image:Sts-50-patch.png|60px]]\n|}}\n'''Lawrence James \"Larry\" DeLucas'''  (O. D., Ph.D.) is an American [[biochemist]] who flew aboard NASA  [[Space Shuttle]] mission [[STS-50]] as a [[Payload Specialist]].  He was born on July 11, 1950 in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and is currently married with three children.  His recreational interests include [[basketball]], [[scuba diving]], [[bowling]], [[Scale model|model]] [[airplane]]s, [[astronomy]] and [[Reading (activity)|reading]].\n\n==Education==\nDeLucas attended the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] (UAB), in [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Alabama]] and received the following degrees:\n*[[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Chemistry]] (1972)\n*[[Master of Science]] degree in [[Chemistry]] (1974)\n*[[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[physiological optics|Physiological Optics]] (1979)\n*[[Doctorate]] in [[Optometry]] (1981)\n*[[Doctorate]] in [[Biochemistry]] (1982)\n\n==Organizations==\nDeLucas has served as a member of the following organizations:\n*[[American Crystallographic Association]]\n*[[American Academy of Optometry]]\n*[[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]]\n*[[Alabama Optometric Association]]\n*[[American Association of Pharmaceutical Scientists]]\n*[[National Aeronautic Association]]\n*[[Biotechnology Industry Organization]]\n*[[Biotechnology Association of Alabama]]\n*[[Helen Keller Eye Research Foundation]]\n\n==Publications==\nHe has published 163 research articles in refereed scientific journals, is co-author of 2 books, and co-inventor on 43 patents.\n\n==Honors==\n* Co-Chair, Spacehab Science Advisory Board\n* Secretary of the Board, Council of Biotechnology Centers, Biotechnology Industry Council\n* Distinguished Faculty Lecturer, UAB\n* Howell Heflin Statesmanship Award for Technology, NASA Space Flight Medal\n* Recognized as one of the scientists who could shape the 21st century in an article by [[The Sunday Times]] entitled \"The Brains Behind the 21st Century\"\n* Distinguished Crystallography Lecturer for Pittsburgh Diffraction Society Lecturers\n* Honorary Doctor of Science degree, The Ohio State University, Illinois College of Optometry, State University of New York State College of Optometry, and Ferris State University, Big Rapids, MI.\n* NASA Space Flight Medal; flew as a payload specialist astronaut on the Columbia Space Shuttle, June 25-July 9, 1992. This was the longest space shuttle flight to date making 221 orbits of Earth.  \n* Served as the NASA Chief Scientist for the International Space Station, at NASA HQ in Washington DC; 1994-1995.\n* Received the 1st Distinguished Alumnus Award from the University of Alabama at Birmingham, December 8, 1991.\n\n==Experience==\n* 1975 \u2013 1976: Research Associate in the Institute of Dental Research, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1977 \u2013 1982: Graduate Student, working on combined doctoral degrees in Optometry and Biochemistry\n* 1982 \u2013 2016: Member of Vision Science Research Center\n* 1983 \u2013 2016: Member, Graduate Faculty, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1984 \u2013 2016: Scientist, Comprehensive Cancer Center, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1986 \u2013 1992: Associate Director, Center for Macromolecular Crystallography, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1987 \u2013 2001: Member of NASA Science Advisory Committee for Advanced Protein Crystal Growth\n* 1989 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Materials Science, [[University of Alabama in Huntsville]], [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]], [[University of Alabama]]\n* 1989 \u2013 2016: Professor, Department of Optometry, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1990 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Laboratory of Medical Genetics, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1990 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Department of Biochemistry, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1990 \u2013 2010: Member, Executive Committee and Board of the Helen Keller Eye Research Foundation\n* 1994 \u2013 1995: NASA Chief Scientist for International Space Station\n* 1994 \u2013 2016: Director, Center for Biophysical Sciences and Engineering, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1994 \u2013 2016: Director, Cancer Center X-ray Core Facility, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1996 \u2013 2016: Member Research Foundation and Technology Transfer Committee, [[University of Alabama at \nBirmingham|UAB]]\n* 1997 \u2013 1998: Member Metabolic Bone Disease, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 1997 \u2013 2000: Member, Media Relations Group, [[University of Alabama at Birmingham|UAB]]\n* 2001 \u2013 2016: Adjunct Professor, Physiology and Biophysics\n* 2016\u2013present: Principal Scientist, The Aerospace Corporation\n\n==Spaceflight==\n[[File:Crewmembers in the spacelab with the Lower Body Negative Pressure Study.jpg|thumb|right|DeLucas and [[Bonnie J. Dunbar]] in Spacelab with the Lower Body Negative Pressure device]]\nDeLucas was a member of the crew of [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']] for STS-50 (June 25-July 9, 1992), the United States Microgravity Laboratory-1 (USML-1) Spacelab mission. Over a two-week period, the crew conducted a wide variety of experiments relating to materials processing and fluid physics. At mission conclusion, DeLucas had traveled over 5.7 million miles in 221 Earth orbits, and had logged over 331 hours in space.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/PS/delucas.html NASA bio of DeLucas]\n*[http://www.spacefacts.de//bios/astronauts/english/delucas_lawrence.htm Spacefacts biography of Lawrence J. DeLucas]\n\n{{Use American English|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Delucas, Lawrence J.}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama at Birmingham alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama in Huntsville faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Syracuse, New York]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:Space Shuttle program astronauts]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonors:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1994-1995 \u2192 1994\u20131995", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lawrence_J._DeLucas"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in France", "text_new": "{{Expand French|Pand\u00e9mie de maladie \u00e0 coronavirus de 2020 en France|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in France}}\n{{Infobox outbreak\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak France per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million inhabitants by region\n| map2            = COVID-19 Outbreak Hospitalized in France 13 Regions & DomTom.svg\n| legend2         = {{center|[[Regions of France]] with number of people currently hospitalised}}\n{{legend|#FCEED3|Hospitalised 1~9}}\n{{legend|#F2A88D|Hospitalised 10~99}}\n{{legend|#E36654|Hospitalised 100~499}}\n{{legend|#E5354B|Hospitalised 500~999}}\n{{legend|#87353F|Hospitalised 1000~9999}}\n{{legend|#630606|Hospitalised \u226510000}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = France\n| first_case      = [[Bordeaux]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China\n| recovery_cases  = 30,955<ref name=\"dashboard Covid19 France\" />\n| deaths          = 17,167 (total)<ref name=\"dashboard Covid19 France\" /> <br> 8,598 (hospital)<ref name=\"dashboard Covid19 France\" /> <br> 4,599 ({{Interlanguage link|EHPAD|fr}})<ref name=\"dashboard Covid19 France\" />\n| confirmed_cases = 106,206<ref name=\"Sant\u00e9 Publique France\">{{cite web|url=https://www.santepubliquefrance.fr/maladies-et-traumatismes/maladies-et-infections-respiratoires/infection-a-coronavirus/articles/infection-au-nouveau-coronavirus-sars-cov-2-covid-19-france-et-monde|title=Sant\u00e9 Publique France|date=10 April 2020|language=fr}}</ref>\n| website         = [https://www.santepubliquefrance.fr/maladies-et-traumatismes/maladies-et-infections-respiratoires/infection-a-coronavirus/articles/infection-au-nouveau-coronavirus-sars-cov-2-covid-19-france-et-monde Public Health France]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|<noinclude>2019\u201320 coronavirus </noinclude>pandemic]] reached [[France]] on 24 January 2020, when the first [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case in Europe and France was confirmed in [[Bordeaux]]. The first five confirmed cases were all individuals who had recently arrived or returned from China.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite news|last1=Jacob|first1=Etienne|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/sciences/coronavirus-trois-premiers-cas-confirmes-en-france-20200124|title=Coronavirus: trois premiers cas confirm\u00e9s en France|date=24 January 2020|work=Le Figaro|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Bernard-Stoecklin|first=S|date=13 February 2020|title=First cases of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) in France: surveillance, investigations and control measures, January 2020|journal=Eurosurveillance|volume=25|issue=6|pages=2000094|doi=10.2807/1560-7917.ES.2020.25.6.2000094|pmid=32070465|pmc=7029452}}</ref> On 28 January, a Chinese tourist carrying the virus was admitted to hospital in Paris and died on 14 February, making it the first death in France.<ref name=\"StraitsTimesFourthCase\">{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/france-confirms-fourth-case-of-coronavirus-in-elderly-chinese-tourist|title=Wuhan virus: France confirms fourth case of coronavirus in elderly Chinese tourist|date=29 January 2020|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220191811/https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/france-confirms-fourth-case-of-coronavirus-in-elderly-chinese-tourist|archive-date=20 February 2020|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-first-case-europe\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51514837|title=First coronavirus death confirmed in Europe|date=15 February 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=27 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219204410/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51514837|archive-date=19 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/29/national/japan-support-for-coronavirus-hit-wuhan/|title=Support efforts begin across Japan to help coronavirus-hit Wuhan|work=[[Japan Times]]|access-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/e96365aa6ba46ba6bef50a0673301985|title=France announces 1st death of virus patient outside Asia|last=Ganley|first=Elaine|date=15 February 2020|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne key event in the spread of the disease across Metropolitan France as well as its overseas territories was the annual assembly of the [[Christian Open Door Church]] between 17 and 24 February in [[Mulhouse]] which was attended by about 2,500 people, at least half of whom are believed to have contracted the virus.<ref name=\"lepoint2369173\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lepoint.fr/sante/coronavirus-la-bombe-atomique-du-rassemblement-evangelique-de-mulhouse-28-03-2020-2369173_40.php|title=Coronavirus : la \" bombe atomique \" du rassemblement \u00e9vang\u00e9lique de Mulhouse|date=28 March 2020|website=Le Point}}</ref><ref name=\"francetvinfo3889133\">{{cite web|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/video-coronavirus-le-nombre-de-contaminations-lors-du-rassemblement-evangelique-de-mulhouse-a-ete-largement-sous-evalue_3889133.html|title=ENQUETE FRANCEINFO. \"La majorit\u00e9 des personnes \u00e9taient contamin\u00e9es\" : de la Corse \u00e0 l'outre-mer, comment le rassemblement \u00e9vang\u00e9lique de Mulhouse a diffus\u00e9 le coronavirus dans toute la France|date=28 March 2020|website=Franceinfo}}</ref>\n\n<onlyinclude>{{#ifeq:{{{transcludesection|FrenchDomesticResponse}}}|FrenchDomesticResponse|\nOn 12 March, French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] announced on public television that all schools and all universities would close from Monday 16 March until further notice. The next day, the prime minister [[\u00c9douard Philippe]] banned gatherings of more than 100 people, not including public transport. The following day, the prime minister ordered the closure of all non-essential public places, including restaurants, caf\u00e9s, cinemas and nightclubs, effective at midnight.<ref name=\"bbc51892477\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-51892477|title=Coronavirus: Spain and France announce sweeping restrictions|work=BBC News|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, President Macron announced mandatory home confinement for 15 days starting at noon on 17 March.<ref name=\"independent9405136\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-france-lockdown-cases-update-covid-19-macron-a9405136.html|title=France imposes 15-day lockdown as part of emergency coronavirus response|date=16 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref>}}</onlyinclude> On 27 March, Prime Minister \u00c9douard Philippe extended the lockdown until 15 April.<ref name=\"independent9405136\"/> On 8 April 2020, President Macron announced the lockdown would be extended once more.<ref>[https://www.france24.com/en/20200408-france-to-extend-coronavirus-lockdown-again-will-run-beyond-april-15 France to extend coronavirus lockdown again, will run beyond April 15] 8 April 2020 ''www.france24.com'', accessed 9 April 2020</ref> On 13 April, he announced that the lock-down period would be extended until 11 May.<ref name=\"macron13april\">{{cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/direct-coronavirus-prolongation-du-confinement-reouverture-des-ecoles-et-des-commerces-regardez-l-allocution-televisee-d-emmanuel-macron_3913673.html|title=Coronavirus : prolongation du confinement jusqu'au 11 mai|date=2020-04-13|publisher=[[France Info (TV channel)|France Info]]|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|4|15|alt=As of 14 April}}, France has reported 106,206 confirmed cases, 17,167 deaths, and 30,955 recoveries,<ref name=\"dashboard Covid19 France\">{{cite web|url=https://dashboard.covid19.data.gouv.fr/|title=COVID-19 en France|publisher=Sant\u00e9 Publique France|language=fr|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> making it the fifth highest country by number of confirmed cases, now overtaking China where the outbreak first began.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/coronavirus-maps.html Coronavirus Map: Tracking the Global Outbreak] ''The New York Times''. Retrieved 4 April 2020</ref> France also counts nursing home deaths since 2 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200403-french-hospitals-record-deadliest-day-with-588-coronavirus-deaths|title=French hospitals record deadliest day with 588 coronavirus deaths|date=3 April 2020|publisher=France 24|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|4|8|alt=As of 8 April}} France has reported 30,902 confirmed or suspected cases in retirement homes. (These figures are now included in the national tally.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.santepubliquefrance.fr/maladies-et-traumatismes/maladies-et-infections-respiratoires/infection-a-coronavirus/articles/infection-au-nouveau-coronavirus-sars-cov-2-covid-19-france-et-monde|title=Infection au nouveau Coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2), COVID-19, France et Monde|website=Sant\u00e9 publique France|language=French|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2020/04/02/au-moins-884-morts-dans-les-maisons-de-retraite-et-ehpad_1784033|title=Covid-19: au moins 884 morts dans les maisons de retraite et Ehpad |website=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|language=French|date=2020-04-02|access-date=2020-04-11|quote=''L\u2019opacit\u00e9 se l\u00e8ve. Alors que de plus en plus de voix s\u2019\u00e9levaient depuis une dizaine de jours pour que la lumi\u00e8re soit faite sur les m\u00e9faits du Covid-19 sur les personnes \u00e2g\u00e9es plac\u00e9es dans des \u00e9tablissements ad hoc (plus de 7 500 sur tout le territoire), les premiers chiffres ont \u00e9t\u00e9 r\u00e9v\u00e9l\u00e9s ce jeudi soir par le directeur g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la Sant\u00e9, J\u00e9r\u00f4me Salomon''}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe pandemic occurred in the backdrop of a protracted [[2019\u201320 French pension reform strike|national protests]] against pension reforms proposed by President [[Emmanuel Macron]] as part of his election manifesto.<ref>{{cite news |title=Macron pension reform: Strike continues for second day |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50682071 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=6 December 2019|date=6 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Amaro |first1=Silvia |title=France's worst strike in decades enters a second day |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/06/france-strikes-for-a-second-day-over-macron-pension-reform-plans.html |publisher=CNBC |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> This is the longest strike in modern French history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50971439|title=French transport strike now longest in 50 years|date=2020-01-02|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en-GB}}</ref> In President Emmanuel Macron's second address to the nation on the pandemic on 16 March, he announced the suspension of all reforms, notably that of pensions.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/coronavirus-la-reforme-des-retraites-suspendue-annonce-macron_fr_5e6fd329c5b60fb69ddc13c9 Coronavirus: la r\u00e9forme des retraites suspendue annonce Macron] 16 March 2020 ''www.huffingtonpost.fr'', accessed 12 April 2020</ref>\n\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref> On 21 January, [[Agn\u00e8s Buzyn]], [[Minister of Health (France)|Minister of Solidarity and Health]] declared that \"The risk of introduction into France is low but it cannot be excluded\". <ref name=\"BuzynJanuary21\">{{cite news|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/sante/coronavirus-le-risque-d-introduction-en-france-est-faible-mais-il-ne-peut-etre-exclu-selon-agnes-buzyn-21-01-2020-8241345.php|title=Coronavirus : \"Le risque d'introduction en France est faible mais il ne peut \u00eatre exclu\", selon Agn\u00e8s Buzyn|date=2020-01-21|publisher=[[Le Parisien]]|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/France medical cases chart}}\n\n===First confirmed cases===\nOn 23 January, the French [[Minister of Health (France)|Minister of Health]] office also officially published the same analysis on the situation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://solidarites-sante.gouv.fr/soins-et-maladies/maladies/maladies-infectieuses/coronavirus/etat-des-lieux-et-actualites/article/points-de-situation-coronavirus-covid-19#Point%20du%2023%20janvier%202020|title=Point du 23 janvier 2020|date=23 January 2020|publisher=[[Minister of Health (France)|French Minister of Health]]|access-date=12 April 2020|quote=''Le risque d'introduction est faible mais ne peut pas \u00eatre exclu.''}}</ref> The same day [[Air France]] suspended its flights from and to [[Wuhan]], and reduced the frequency of its flights from and to Beijing and Shanghai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.europe1.fr/international/coronavirus-air-france-suspend-ses-vols-vers-wuhan-et-reduit-ceux-vers-pekin-et-shanghai-3946372|title=Coronavirus : Air France suspend ses vols vers Wuhan et r\u00e9duit ceux vers P\u00e9kin et Shanghai|date=29 January 2020|publisher=[[Europe 1]]|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January, the first COVID-19 case in Europe was confirmed in [[Bordeaux]]. A 48-year-old French citizen from China, who arrived in France on 22 January, was hospitalised at Centre Hospitalier Universitaire de Bordeaux. [[Service d'Aide M\u00e9dicale Urgente]] took charge and the patient was isolated in the hospital. The authorities tried to confirm whether he had infected people who were in contact with him.<ref name=\"francetvinfo3799837\">{{cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-en-france-le-parcours-des-trois-patients_3799837.html|title=Coronavirus en France : le parcours des trois patients|date=24 January 2020|work=France Info|access-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221231826/https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-en-france-le-parcours-des-trois-patients_3799837.html|archive-date=21 February 2020|language=fr}}</ref>. Agn\u00e8s Buzyn then said that \"The risks of propagation of the virus in France are extremely low\".<ref name=\"BuzynJanuary24\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/mediaplayer/video/coronavirus-en-france-les-risques-de-propagation-du-virus-dans-la-population-sont-tres-faibles-selon-agnes-buzyn-1217484.html|title=Coronavirus : en France, \"les risques de propagation du virus dans la population sont tr\u00e8s faibles\" selon Agn\u00e8s Buzyn|date=24 January 2020|publisher=[[BFM TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Two more cases were confirmed in Paris by the end of the day \u2013 a couple who had returned from China on 18 January.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-outbreak-hospital-to-be-built-in-five-days-as-death-toll-rises-in-china-11916211|title=Coronavirus outbreak: First confirmed cases in Europe as France declares two infections|publisher=Sky News|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lemonde6027158\">{{cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/01/24/coronavirus-deux-premiers-cas-confirmes-en-france-a-bordeaux-et-paris_6027158_3244.html|title=Coronavirus : deux premi\u00e8res contaminations confirm\u00e9es en France|date=24 January 2020|work=Le Monde|access-date=24 January 2020|language=fr}}</ref> The 31-year-old man and his 30-year-old partner, both from [[Wuhan]], tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 and were hospitalised at [[Bichat\u2013Claude Bernard Hospital]] in Paris. On 26 January, Buzyn declared that the French government had millions of masks which could be distributed to the population if necessary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liberation.fr/checknews/2020/02/27/covid-19-y-a-t-il-une-penurie-de-masques-de-protection_1779861|title=Covid-19 : y a-t-il une p\u00e9nurie de masques de protection pour les professionnels de sant\u00e9? |date=27 January 2020|work=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bfmtv.com/mediaplayer/video/coronavirus-agnes-buzyn-estime-totalement-inutile-le-port-de-masque-pour-les-non-contamines-1217820.html|title=Coronavirus: Agn\u00e8s Buzyn estime \"totalement inutile\" le port de masque pour les non-contamin\u00e9s |date=26 January 2020|publisher=[[BFM TV]]|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, an 80-year-old Chinese tourist from Hubei tested positive and was hospitalised at Bichat\u2013Claude Bernard Hospital,<ref name=\"StraitsTimesFourthCase\" /> the following day, his 50-year-old daughter tested positive and was admitted to the same hospital.<ref name=\"lexpress2116745\">{{cite web |title=Cinqui\u00e8me case aver\u00e9 |url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/societe/sante/coronavirus-un-cinquieme-cas-avere-en-france-la-fille-du-quatrieme-malade_2116745.html |website=L'Express |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=29 January 2020 |language=fr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129193013/https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/societe/sante/coronavirus-un-cinquieme-cas-avere-en-france-la-fille-du-quatrieme-malade_2116745.html |archive-date=29 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The death of the 80-year-old on 14 February marked the first death from COVID-19 outside of Asia.<ref name=\"BBC-first-case-europe\" />\n\nOn 30 January, a Paris doctor who had come into contact with a Chinese tourist whose infection was confirmed upon her return to China was confirmed positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"leparisien8248956\">{{cite web|title=Coronavirus: un sixi\u00e8me cas confirm\u00e9|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/coronavirus-un-sixieme-cas-confirme-en-france-un-medecin-confine-a-paris-30-01-2020-8248956.php|website=[[Le Parisien]]|accessdate=30 January 2020|date=30 January 2020|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131112945/http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/coronavirus-un-sixieme-cas-confirme-en-france-un-medecin-confine-a-paris-30-01-2020-8248956.php|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, the [[Direction g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la sant\u00e9]] (DGS) asked ''Sant\u00e9 publique France'' to buy ''urgently'' 1,1&nbsp;million of [[FFP mask#FFP2 mask|FFP2 mask]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Masques: les preuves d'un mensonge d'Etat |url=https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/france/020420/masques-les-preuves-d-un-mensonge-d-etat|website=[[Mediapart]]|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020|language=fr|quote=''Le 24 janvier, la Direction g\u00e9n\u00e9rale de la sant\u00e9 (DGS) saisit l\u2019agence Sant\u00e9 publique France (SPF), sous la tutelle du minist\u00e8re, pour faire un inventaire des stocks de mat\u00e9riel m\u00e9dical. Le 30 janvier, elle lui demande d'acqu\u00e9rir \u00ab d\u00e8s que possible \u00bb 1,1 million de masques FFP2 seulement, selon un document obtenu par Mediapart''}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, Marie Fontanel, the President counselor for solidarity and health, quit her job to help her husband in the coming municipal elections. She would be replaced only one month later.<ref>{{cite web|title=L'\u00e9tonnant d\u00e9part de la conseill\u00e8re sant\u00e9 d'Emmanuel Macron  |url=https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/france/050420/l-etonnant-depart-de-la-conseillere-sante-d-emmanuel-macron|website=[[Mediapart]]|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=13 April 2020|language=fr|quote=''Conseill\u00e8re sant\u00e9 du pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique depuis le d\u00e9but du quinquennat, Marie Fontanel a quitt\u00e9 l\u2019\u00c9lys\u00e9e le 31 janvier, alors que l\u2019OMS venait de d\u00e9clarer \u00ab l\u2019urgence de sant\u00e9 publique de port\u00e9e internationale \u00bb. Elle n\u2019a \u00e9t\u00e9 remplac\u00e9e qu\u2019un mois plus tard. Cette vacance interroge de nouveau sur la gestion de la crise sanitaire par le pouvoir, au moment o\u00f9 la menace pand\u00e9mique se profilait d\u00e9j\u00e0.''}}</ref> The same day, all the countries of the [[Schengen Area]], except France, suspend [[Travel visa|visas]] with China.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confirmed: All Schengen Countries, but France, Have Suspended Visa Issuance in China|url=https://www.schengenvisainfo.com/news/confirmed-all-schengen-countries-but-france-have-suspended-visa-issuance-in-china/|website=[[Mediapart]]|accessdate=13 April 2020|date=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\" style=\"margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;\"\n|-\n!Case